{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505440"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:30:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:30:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2443"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2443"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.22,0.08,0.4,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2443"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104522"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2443"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2443"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86849"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"11696"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26291"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104522"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a nosebleed that started after being hit by a cricket ball. The bleeding has persisted despite 30 minutes of direct pressure. She reports a history of recurrent epistaxis and heavy menstrual bleeding. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There are scattered ecchymoses on her arms and legs. Abdominal examination reveals no organomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 125 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 9.1 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (3.6-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 15 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (140-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActivated partial thromboplastin time 29 seconds (30-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProthrombin time 58 seconds (60-70)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeripheral blood film shows normal platelet morphology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management in addition to local measures for epistaxis control?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Corticosteroids","Intravenous immunoglobulin","Clinical observation","Platelet transfusion","Romiplostim"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of immune thrombocytopenia (ITP): mucosal bleeding, scattered ecchymoses, and isolated severe thrombocytopenia with normal platelet morphology. The absence of hepatosplenomegaly and normal white cell count help distinguish this from other causes of thrombocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are the first-line treatment for ITP when there is active bleeding or the platelet count is below 20-30 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L. They work by reducing antibody production and decreasing platelet destruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for life-threatening bleeding or when rapid platelet increment is required (e.g., pre-surgery). This patient is haemodynamically stable with non-severe bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClinical observation\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be appropriate for asymptomatic patients with platelet counts above 30 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L. This patient has active bleeding and requires intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E alone is generally ineffective in ITP as transfused platelets are rapidly destroyed by the same autoantibodies that are destroying the patient\u0027s own platelets.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERomiplostim\u003C/strong\u003E is a thrombopoietin receptor agonist that stimulates platelet production. It is typically reserved for chronic ITP that has failed to respond to first-line treatments. It would not be appropriate as initial therapy in this newly presenting case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Corticosteroids are first-line treatment for immune thrombocytopenia with active bleeding or platelets \u003C20-30 x10^9 /L","Platelet transfusion alone is ineffective in immune thrombocytopenia due to rapid destruction by autoantibodies","Thrombopoietin receptor agonists are typically reserved for chronic ITP refractory to first-line therapy"],"references":["Provan D, Arnold DM, Bussel JB, Chong BH, Cooper N, Gernsheimer T, Ghanima W, Godeau B, Gonz\u00e1lez-L\u00f3pez TJ, Grainger J, Hou M, Kruse C, McDonald V, Michel M, Newland AC, Pavord S, Rodeghiero F, Scully M, Tomiyama Y, Wong RS, Zaja F, Kuter DJ. Updated international consensus report on the investigation and management of primary immune thrombocytopenia. Blood Adv. 2019 Nov 26;3(22):3780-3817.","Choi PY, Merriman E, Bennett A, Enjeti AK, Tan CW, Goncalves I, et al. Consensus guidelines for the management of adult immune thrombocytopenia in Australia and New Zealand. Med J Aust [Internet]. 2021 Oct 11 [cited 2025 Jan 2];216(1). Available from: https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2022/216/1/consensus-guidelines-management-adult-immune-thrombocytopenia-australia-and-new"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86849"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2443"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86849"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T12:59:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T13:00:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2443"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104522"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"